{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625570"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:26:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:26:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17036"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17036"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.49,0.05,0.34,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68779"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9726"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17036"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5286"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23059"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68779"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with abdominal pain and diarrhoea. Stool microscopy reveals eggs consistent with hookworm infection. The doctor prescribes albendazole.  Albendazole is a broad-spectrum antihelmintic and antiprotozoal agent of the benzimidazole class.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the therapeutic use of this class of drugs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibition of ergosterol synthesis in fungi","Disruption of helminth microtubule formation","Inhibition of bacterial cell wall synthesis","Disruption of protozoan membrane integrity","Interference with viral DNA polymerase"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBenzimidazoles cause \u003Cstrong\u003Edisruption of helminth microtubule formation\u003C/strong\u003E by binding to parasite \u03b2-tubulin. This prevents cell division and leads to parasite death. Common examples include albendazole and mebendazole which are highly effective against intestinal nematodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of ergosterol synthesis in fungi\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of azole antifungals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of bacterial cell wall synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is how beta-lactam antibiotics work. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of protozoan membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of antiprotozoal drugs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterference with viral DNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of certain antivirals like aciclovir.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBenzimidazoles are particularly effective because they bind more strongly to parasite tubulin than human tubulin, providing selective toxicity. This makes them safe and effective treatments for intestinal worm infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benzimidazole anthelmintics work by binding to parasite \u03b2-tubulin, disrupting microtubule formation and cell division.","Common benzimidazole drugs include albendazole and mebendazole, used to treat intestinal worm infections.","Benzimidazoles have broad-spectrum activity against many helminth species with minimal toxicity to human cells."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54236"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17036"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54236"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T15:42:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T15:42:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9726"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68779"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and re